Reason For Visit Patient presents for sore throat.
HPI: KATE reports 3-4 day history of sore throat, saw her dentist who thought she might have early cold sores on the roof of her mouth. These appear to progressed to involve the left side of her throat with some mild pain with swallowing. She's had no fever or chills, no cough or congestion.
ALLERGIES: ACE Inhibitors; Angioedema amlodipine Cephalosporins Erythromycin Derivatives Keflex TABS Penicillins Pneumovax 23 INJ; Adverse Reaction; Myalgia,Paresthesia,Rash.
CURRENT MEDS: Liothyronine Sodium 5 MCG Oral Tablet;Take 2 each morning.; RPT Camrese 0.15-0.03 &0.01 MG Oral Tablet;TAKE 1 TABLET DAILY.; Rx ProAir HFA 108 (90 Base) MCG/ACT Inhalation Aerosol Solution;INHALE 1 TO 2 PUFFS EVERY 4 TO 6 HOURS AS NEEDED.; Rx Levothyroxine Sodium 50 MCG Oral Tablet;TAKE 1 TABLET BY MOUTH ONCE DAILY; Rx Losartan Potassium-HCTZ 100-25 MG Oral Tablet;TAKE 1 TABLET BY MOUTH ONCE DAILY; Rx.
PERSONAL HX: Alcohol; rarely Marital History - Single Never a smoker Occupation:; works at county parks.

PHYSICAL EXAM: Alert and comfortable HEENT: Oropharynx moist, there are erythematous macules on the left hard palate, with mild diffuse left tonsillar edema and erythema, no exudates, no ulcerations. Neck: Mild tender left submandibular and anterior cervical adenopathy Clear to auscultation Regular rate no murmur.

PLAN: Reviewed negative strep findings, findings are consistent with likely viral pharyngitis for which supportive measures and good hygiene are recommended along with follow-up in 7-10 days if not significantly improved. Portable measures discussed.

RE: BENTLEY, KATE A MRN: 032775 ACCOUNT NUMBER: 57102090016
DATE: 05/26/2016
DOMINICAN HAND REHABILITATION CENTER INITIAL EVALUATION
DIAGNOSIS: Right wrist pain/right finger tenosynovitis.
Date of injury: March 2016 Date of evaluation: May 26, 2016.
Dear Dr. Joy,
Thank you for referring your patient to the Dominican Hand Rehabilitation Center. She presented today for evaluation. Listed below are the findings.
MEDICAL HISTORY: The patient reports that in approximately March 2016 she hit the dorsum of her hand between the 4th and 5th metacarpals when she was pulling an object off a shelf. At that time she had a contusion and she was seen here in the Hand Clinic following that contusion for pain and limitation in range of motion. She had good resolution at that time but reports the symptoms have reoccurred in her forearm area.
PRIOR LEVEL OF FUNCTION: The patient was independent at home and in the community without pain or limitation. She is right-hand dominant.
PRIOR MEDICAL HISTORY: Significant for a history of chemotherapy when she was much younger. She did receive chemotherapy in the right arm at that time and does complain of peripheral neuropathy in all fingertips and toes.
ACTIVE RANGE OF MOTION: Bilateral shoulder, elbow and forearm range of motion is grossly within functional limits. Specific measurements for the right wrist extension/flexion are 65/79 degrees, left 75/80 degrees respectively. Composite wrist extension/flexion, on the right measured 50 degrees for extension with a tight feeling and for composite flexion on the right was 72 degrees again with a tight sensation over the dorsum of the hand. Composite wrist extension/flexion on the left, measurements were 70/67 degrees respectively. Digit range of motion was grossly within functional limits.
PAIN: Patient reports most pain as a burning, throbbing type of sensation located in the ulnar aspect of her distal medial forearm.
SENSATION: Patient reports some pins and needle sensations with forearm palpation, also reports altered sensation throughout her arm with most of this located on the medial ulnar aspect of the forearm but with some altered sensation over the hypothenar eminence as well as the thenar eminence and some more proximal toward the medial epicondyle.
APPEARANCE: Patient's right forearm appears slightly more raised on the volar ulnar margin distally.
STRENGTH: General strength measurements of intrinsic strength of the digits indicated a generally weaker left hand than the right hand.
SPECIFIC STRENGTH MEASUREMENTS: right grip measured 33 pounds with 4/10 pain at the hypothenar on the right,on the left 45 pounds. Three-point pinch: Right 14 pounds, left 14.5 pounds. Lateral pinch: Right 12 pounds, left 15 pounds.
ADL/PROBLEM ACTIVITIES: The patient scored a 71.5 on the PRWE and the patient-rated wrist/hand evaluation indicating patient feels she has approximately a 71-1/2% disability as a result of this injury. Specifically the patient has minimal difficulty with buttoning and cutting, moderate difficulty with door knobs and toilet tissue and general household tasks as well as recreational activities and severe difficulty with carrying objects, pushing up from the floor and performing work tasks.
IMPRESSION: Patient presents with a history of right dorsal hand contusion with residual effects of pain and paresthesia of the forearm, also prior history of chemo delivery in the right arm and resulting neuropathy in all fingers and toes.
PROBLEM LIST AND THERAPY DIAGNOSIS: Includes decreased range of motion, decreased strength, pain impaired sensation, and limitation in ADLs.
TREATMENT GOALS: Increase range of motion, increase strength, decrease pain and edema, to provide protective and functional splints as necessary, for patient be independent in functional hand use for toileting hygiene without pain or limitation, for patient to be independent in home program and symptom control, for patient return to work and avocational activities using adaptive and protective techniques and having less pain.
TREATMENT PLAN: Treatment is recommended 1-2 times per week for 12 weeks to include active, active assistive and passive range of motion, joint mobilization upper arm forearm wrist and hand strengthening pain, control program, ADL and work training, splinting training and taping, home exercise program, patient education and modalities to include hot packs, ultrasound, iontophoresis, cold packs, electrical stimulation, paraffin, TENS, fluidotherapy, contrast bath and light therapy.
If you have any questions or concerns regarding this patient or evaluation please contact the Hand Rehabilitation Center at (831) 457-7130. Thank you again for this referral.
